{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1938010901/0719.xml":{"full_text":"FINANCIAL AND MARKET\nSUMMARY OF WEEK\nPART FOUR\u2014FINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\nCLASSIFIED ADVERTISING\nPAGES FIVE TO FOURTEEN\nFOURTEEN PAGES.\nWASHINGTON, D. C., JANUARY 9, 1938.\nHOLLAND NAMED\nCONVENTION CHIEF\nOF D1C1BANKERS\nPost Generally Considered\nas First Step Toward\nPresidency.\nROSENBERG APPOINTED\nGROUP VICE CHAIRMAN\n\nMilton H. Prosperi Is Elected\nBoard Chairman of American\nBuilding Association.\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nT. Stanley Holland, trust officer of\nthe American Security Trust Co.,\nhas been appointed general conven- J\ntion chairman of the 20th annual j\nconclave of the District of Columbia\nBankers\u2019 Association, to be held at\nhoc springs, va,\nthe last of May.\nIt was announced\nyesterday by\nPresident Thom\nas G. Groom.\nThis is the\nmost important\nappointment in\nconnection with\nthe forthcoming\nconvention. His\ncommittee aids\nwill be named\nshortly. The new\nchairman is a\nnative Washing\ntonian, educated\nJ. Stanley Holland, j\nin the public schools, and a graduate\nof Georgetown University Law School.\nHe has been active in the financial j\ndistrict for the past 30 years, and\nhas rendered valuable service to the\nassociation as chairman of the Fiduci\naries Committee, chairman of the\nAdvertising Committee, member of\nthe Council of Administration and\n'vice president of the Trust Company\nDivision of the association.\nYesterday\u2019s appointment is consid\nered of much more than ordinary in\nterest because in the past, the general\nconvention chairman has usually been\nelected a vice president of the asso\nciation at the conclusion of the con\nvention session. This means that\nthe chairman usually becomes presi\ndent of the association four years\nlater, an honor coveted by many j\nbankers.\nPresident Groom also announced\nthe appointment of Maurice D. Rosen\nberg. president of the Bank of Com- j\nrnerce and Savings, as vice chairman\nof the Convention Committee. Mr. j\nRosenberg, a former president of the\nr bankers\u2019 association, has been prom-\nlnently identified with civic and\nfinancial affairs of the District for j\nmany years, and has served as presi- j\ndent of the Bank of Commerce and j\nBavings since its inception 30 years\n\u2022go.\nProsper! New Board Chairman.\nMilton H. Prosperi has been elected\nehairman of the Board of Directors\nof the American Building Association,\nS0O Pennsylvania avenue S.E., a newly\nM. H. Prosperi.\nCl I'M Leu pUMUUll.\nit was announced\nyesterday. A\nwidely kno w n\nWashington phy\nsician, he has\nserved on the as\nsociation's direc\ntorate for many\nyears.\nAll other offi\ncers and direc-\ntors were re\nelected at the\nannual meeting\nheld Friday.\nCharles Kattel- j\nmann was again\ncnosen president. Artnur C. Balser,\n*ice president; Wilfred H. Blanz, sec-\nfetary, and Guy M. Neely, treasurer.\nThe Board of Directors is composed\nof John E. Mergner, Clarence F. i\nDonohoe, Chatham M. Towers, Thomas\nS. Sergeon, Charles A. Rossiter, Dr.\nProsperi, Dr. William C. Farmer and\nCharles H. Kindle. j\nThe official staff was expanded by\nelection of Howard B. Kramer assist-\nant secretary and R. Lee Baxter as- j\n\u2022istant treasurer. The board declared\na 4 per cent dividend, same as the j\nassociation paid last year, and added\n$100,000 to surplus. It was reported j\nthat assets now total more than I\n$10,000,000.\nFollowing the annual meeting, the\ndirectors and personnel held a dinner\nlast night at the Continental Hotel,\nat which H. H. McKee, president of\nthe National Capital Bank and chair\nman of the Washington Clearing\nBouse Association, was the guest\napeaker, and Dr. Prosperi toastmaster.\nFifth District Trade Rises.\nWith the exception of Washington,\nWhere there was a decrease of 3.31\nper cent, retail trade in the Fifth\nReserve District last week showed a\nmoderate increase over the corre\naponding week a year ago, the Com\nmerce Department reported yesterday\nto surveying conditions in 36 cities.\nMerchants in the Capital reported\ndeclines from minus 17 per cent to\nplus 12 per cent.\nWashington bank clearings were\nlower than in the same week last\nyear. Building permits totaled $208.\n750 during the week and for the\nmonth of December, 1937, amounted\nto $940,475, against $2,455,335 in\nDecember, 1936, the Commerce report\nstated.\nExchange Trading hteps Up.\nIn the first week of 1938 trading\non the Washington Stock Exchange\nrevealed improvement in volume. Cap\nital Traction 5s figured in seven $1,000\ntransactions, all at 65. At this low\nt mark the bonds return the very high\nyield of 11.35 per cent.\nWashington Gas 5s, 1960, were in\ndemand at 116 and 115%, while the\nsame corporation $4.50 preferred stock\nmoved at 97 and 97 li. Capital Transit\nstock stepped up to 9% on one sale\nduring the week.\nIn the Saturday market a lone\nshare of Capital Transit came out at\n8 and there were four consecutive\n100-share sales in Real Estate Mort\ngage Guaranty preferred stock\nat 4\\.\nUnited Corp. Uncertain\nOn Registration Plans\nConferences With S. E. C. Followed by\nReports That Holding Giant Is\nPreparing to Comply.\nBy me Associate press.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8.\u2014The United\nCorp., $581,000,000 Morgan-sponsored\nutility investment company with large\nholdings in major Eastern power sys\ntems, has been discussing registra\ntion with the S. E. C. under the Pub\nlic Utility Holding Co, Act but\nhas made no decision, it was said in\ninformed circles today.\nConferences between United and\nS. E. C. officials at Washington had\nbeen followed by conjecture in Wall\nStreet as to whether the giant invest\nment unit, together with several other\nlarge utility combines, was planning\nto comply with the requirement of\nthe act for registration of holders of\nCOTTON REMAINS\nIN NARROW RANGE\nAT WEEK\u2019S CLOSE\nFinal Prices Are Steady to\nThree Points Higher as\nBuying Lags.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8.\u2014Cotton moved\nover a narrow range today as trade\nand commission house buying en\ncountered hedge selling and liquida\ntion. March fluctuated between 8.47\nand 8.50. closing at 8.49, with final\nprices net unchanged to 3 points\nhigher.\nOrders were about evenly divided\nand during the entire session fluc\ntuations were limited to within a\nrange of 2 to 8 points. Steadiness ot\nthe stock market helped the under\ntone. but there was no very aggres\nsive buying.\nCommodity Credit Corporation re\nported 4.427.930 bales pledged to the\ncotton loan through January 6. The\namount of cotton on shipboard await\ning clearance at the close of the\nweek was estimated at 100.000 bales,\nagainst 158.000 last year and 143,000\ntwo years ago.\nThe range follows:\nHigh Low Last\nJanuary .-..8.45 8.43 8.44-45\nMarch .8.50 8.47 8.49-50\nMay -.1.-8.5B 8.53 8.55-58\nJ'-ily ..8.65 8.57 8.63-64\nOctober 8.71 8.67 8.70\nDecember _8.73 8.70 8.72N\nSpot steady; middling 8.59.\nN\u2014Nominal.\nCottonseed Oil.\nCottonseed oil was firmer today on\nrenewed covering and buying by I\nhouses with Eastern and Southern\nconnections. Final prices were 7 to\n10 points net higher, with sales of 150 I\ncontracts. Bleachable spot nominal;\nJanuary closed 7.37, March 7.45, Mav\n7.49, July 7.51.\nXew Orleans Priees. I\nNEW ORLEANS. Jan. X (Ei.\u2014Cotton fu\ntures closed Steady at net advances of 3\nto points.\nOpen. High. Low. Close.\nJanuary x.fi.'t x.5:t X.51 X oil\nMarch X.U! X.H4 x.til x.ti.-f\nMay x.tix X.T1 S.M7 S.xn-71\nJuly _ S.;i s.7; S7J x 70\nOctober _ x.j r X.X2 x.7 7 x v\nDecember X.X! s.S7 x.M X.X7 I\nCottonseed oil closed steady: bleachable\nprune summer yellow 7.25 nominal: prime\ncrude. H.OO-6.12'2. January. 7.02b:\nMarch 7.0:tb: May 7.lob: Julv, 7,t:!b;\nSeptember. 7.15b; October. 7.20b.\nb \u2014Bid.\nHUGE GAIN SEEN\nIN WHEAT EXPORTS\nTotal Reaches 34,783.000 Bushels,'\nAgainst 4,996,000 in Same\nPeriod Last Season.\nB\\ the Associated Press.\nThe Bureau of Agricultural Eco\nnomics reported yesterday that ex\nports of American wheat so far this\nseason amounted to 34,783,000 bushels,\nIncluding flour, compared with 4,996,\n000 for the same period last season,\nwhen supplies were cut short by the\ndrought.\nDuring the same period Canadian\nexports dropped from 153,179,000\nbushels to 58,783,000, Argentine from\n35,356,000 to 19,892,000 and total Euro\npean shipments from 186,488,000 to\n164,688.000.\nThe bureau reported American bar\nley exports at 7,018,000 bushels and\noats at 4,978,000 bushels so far this\nseason.\nProspects for purchase of any con\nsiderable quantity of American wheat\nby Oriental nations continued uncer\ntain, the bureau said, because of mili\ntary activities and governmental con\ntrol of exchange in Japan.\nJapan, however, was reported to be\nexpanding her flour markets in North\nChina. Japanese flour exports during\nthe July-October period were said to\nhave totaled 656,000 barrels, or more\nthan twice as much as in the corre\nsponding period in 1936.\nI---\u2014\n10 per cent or more of the voting\nshares of power properties.\nRepresentatives of United Corp., it\nwas explained, had been talking over\nwith S. E. C. authorities other mat\nters than registration. There had\nbeen some doubt in financial circles\nwhether it would register or divest\nitself of part of its interests to escape\ndesignation as a holding company.\nMajor holdings include common\nstocks amounting to 26 per cent in\nterest in United Gas Improvement\nCo., 22 per cent in Niagara Hudson\nPower Corp., 21 per cent in Columbia\nGas Electric Corp., 18 per cent in\nPublic Service Corp. of New Jersey,\n5 per cent 4n Commonwealth South\nern and 2 per cent In Consolidated\nEdison of New York.\nWHEAT FUMES\nMOUNT SHARPLY\nIN EINAl RALLY\n__\nGains of More Than a Cent\nExtend Week\u2019s Rise\nAbove 7 Cents.\nBY FRANKLIN MULLIN'.\nAssociated ^ress Financial Writer.\nCHICAGO, Jan. 8\u2014The highest\nwheat prices since last October were\nchalked up here today in a final hour\nrally that wiped out earlier losses in\nthe market.\nNet gains of more than 1 cent a\nbushel extended the week's upturn\nin wheat to more than 7 cents.\nAn advance of to 3% in Winni\npeg wheat stimulated the buying here\nalong with strength in securities at\nNew York. Most of the gain at Win\nnipeg was registered by October wheat,\nreflecting continued export demand\nfor Canadian grain for late shipment.\nIt was estimated 1.000.000 bushels of\nNo. 1 and No. 3 Northern Canadian\nwheat was sold late yesterday as far\nahead as December shipment and ad\nditional sales were reported today for\nOctober shipment.\nSharp Rise Recorded.\nWheat closed higher than\nyesterday's finish, May, 97E4-7s; July,\n91a\u00bb-s\u00bb; September, 90a*-'/2; corn\nwas V* off to up; May and July.\n\u2022S%-s4; September, 62?,; oats, r-s\nhigher; May, 32:;4; rye, 1\u20194 up, May,\n77*/2; lard, 12-20 up.\nProfit taking caused wheat to sink\nfractionally to early lows of 95'\u2019s for\nMay and 89* i for July, but around\nmidsession the market began to rally.\nIn the final hour recovery prices rose\nmore than 2 cents from the lows and\nfinished at the highs.\nPrice changes in foreign markets\nwere small, Liverpool futures closing\nunchanged to -V cent higher. Hedg\ning of Australian wheat at Liverpool\nwas believed responsible for failure\nto reflect North American strength.\nAustralian Surplus Larger.\nAustralia, which is competing with\nthe United States for European trade,\nhas an estimated exportable surplus\nmore than 20.000.000 bushels larger\nthan a year ago.\nNumerous commission house ad\nvices to buy on wheat market dips\nhere apparently honeycombed the pit\nwith purchase orders at a slight re\ncession. This advice for the mast part\nwas based on the week's revival in\nexport business. Export sales of North\nAmerican wheat overnight were placed\nat about 750,000 bushels, including\nsome domestic hard winter grain.\nThe unsettled com market reflected\n1T\u00bb cents decline at Buenos Aires and\nreports of Argentine rains, which\nmight check corn deterioration. Export1\nsales were estimated at 300,000 to\n500,000 bushels.\nOats and rye and lard Armed with\nwheat.\nGrain range at principal markets\ntoday:\n_ Prev.\nT MARCH WHEAT-*' C,\u00b0Se' Cl0Se'\n^aTWhU5!^313\u2019* 114\u2019\u00ab ]4'*\nChicago .07% .05% .07\u2019, .06%-**\nM\u2018nne\u00bbP' 1-07 1.04% 1.06% 1.05\nWinnipeg7 1 i'UM* libs'2 lopa,- Topi*-'*\nL1VJu\u00a3y01 WHEATS14'2 1 1B\u2019'\u00ab 1]4\u2019\u00ab\nChicago .01% .80% 01% sn\u2019i-on\nMinneap's 1.03% 1.071, l'o\n\u00bb1\u00ab6 1 -gas i:$?%Y&U\nChicago ,00-j .88 .00% .88%-%\n\"WSbiiT* \u202208,i 101,2\nKans.*city iJg* ^r%\nJULY CORN\u2014\nChicago .\u00ab:t .07% .67% .67%-%\nKans City .60 .50% .60 ,oo\nMAY OATS\nChicago ..77s, .37% .32% 3\u2018\u2019%_V,\nMmr.eap's .70\u2019, .70% \"o\u2019, \u2022'\u2019O\u2019.\nWinnipeg .50% .50% .50% i50%\nIhieaga Cash Market.\nsnv\"^' n>\u00b0 **'ts Corn No 3. mixpd.\n5? 5iiNo' A'.Tell?w\u2019 ,fl2%: No. 3. white.\n61-61%. Oats. No 1. white. 35\u2019 -36%.\n\u00ae2?, b*f?si\u201eNo' 3- yellow. 04%. Barley,\nfeed. 43-67: malting. 70-03. Timothy\nseed. 2.60-05: red clover, 30.00-35.00:\nsweet clover, 0.26-10.00.\n_ Winnipeg Cash Market.\nWINNIPEG. Jan. 8 OPi.\u2014Cash wheat.\nNo. 1. Northern. 1 53%: No. 2. 1.44%; No.\n3, 1.26%. Oats. No. 2. white, 57%; No.\n\u2022it 50%.\nWeekly Financial High Lights\nBy the Associated Press This week. Prev. week. Year ago.\nBrokers\u2019 loans $674,000 *719,000 $1,042,000\nHoldings D. 8. Securities. 2,564,015 2,564,015 2,430,227\nGold reserve 9,119,892 9,120,391 8,851,383\nRediscounts 11,080 12,847 3,041\nBank clearings. 5,810,966 4,992,042 6,538,195\nElectric output (kilowatt hours)\nweek ended January 1*. 2,000,000a 2,085,186 2,080,954\nRepeating electric output (kilowatt\nhours) week ended January 1*. 2,000,000a 2,085,186 2,080,954\n(Final three ciphers omitted in above.)\nCar loadings, week ended Jan. 1. 457,359 460,367 588,263\nCrude oil products (barrels) _ 3,436,600 3,492,600 3,121,400\nStock sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... 6.050.640 7397,505 13,028,555\nBond sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... $37,716,150 $43,813,500 $97,136,000\nNew financing 6,911,000 11,123,000 38,170,525\nFederal Reserve ratio_ 80.0% 80.1% 80.3%\nSteel output rate. 25.6% 19.2% 79.4%\nCall money rate_ 1% 1% 1%\nTime money rate__ 114-114% 1%-U&% 1*4%\nCommercial paper .1- 1% 1%\n\u2022Estimate. aReriaed.\nSTOCKS ADVANCE\nSteels, Motors, Coppers\nand Specialties Close\nNear Day\u2019s Peaks.\nEXPORT COPPER BOOST\nHELPS METAL SHARES\nResumptions at Chrysler and Ford\nPlants Bolster Sentiment.\nBonds Also Improve.\nBy FREDERICK GARDNER,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8\u2014The stock\nmarket chalked oft the Initial week\nof 1938 w'ith the first general ad\nvance in more than a month.\nThe list finished the starting lap\nof the new year today with industrial\nfavorites pushing up 1 to more than\n3 points.\nIn dealings that were not excep\ntionally lively, motors, steels, coppers\nand specialties pushed forward from\nthe start and, despite late profit\nrealizing, most ended around best\nlevels of the day.\nThe Associated Press average of\n60 stocks was up 1 point at 46.6 in\nthe two-hour proceedings. On the\nweek this composite showed a net\ngain of 3.6 points. It was the largest\nupturn for any week since October 30.\nTransfers totaled 779,010 shares. Vol\nume for the latest six days was con\nsiderably under that for the preceding\nperiod.\nAuto Workers Recalled.\nAnnouncements that Chrysler wa*\nTecalling 55.000 employes to resume\nwork on new car assemblies January\n11, and that Ford was putting 25.000\nmore men to work January 17 bol\nstered sentiment.\nAt the same time General Motors\nshipments for December disclosed an\nexceptionally sharp drop. But this\nwas offset by the fact distribution\nfor 1937 was 3.7 per cent ahead of\nthe year before.\nAnother rise in export copper aided\nred metal shares. Steels were in front\ndespite predictions next week's mill\noperations would show a slight de\ncline Helpful to both steels and\ncoppers, as well as others, were\nthoughts of a huge rearmament pro\ngram coming up before Congress in\nthe near future.\nOutstandiag share gainers on the\nday were United States Steel, at 59%:\nBethlehem. 63%; Chrysler, 55%; Gen\neral Motors. 35; Anaconda, 35%; Ken\nnecott, 42: Westinghouse, 106%:\nUnited States Rubber, 27%: Sears\nRoebuck, 62: Santa Fe, 38%; New\nYork Central, 18%; American Tele\nphone, 149%, and Paramount, 12%.\nBonds Forge Upward.\nAdvances were scored all along the\nline in the bond market. Best per\nformances were turned in by some of\nthe low-priced rails and other issue*\nrecently under pressure.\nUnited States Governments, while\nsteady, did little either way and there\nwas little trading. Advances ranged\nup A) 3-32 of a point and losses\nas much.\nProgress in the corporate section\nwas accompanied by light dealings.\nTransfers of all bonds totaled $3,982.\n250, compared with $3,872,800 on Sat\nurday. December 18. the last short\nsession before the holidays.\nThe Associated Press averages were\nuniformly higher, except for the low\nyield group, which, like Govern\nments, was steady but quiet, with the\naverages holding at Friday's close.\nSeveral issues of Lehigh Valley Coal\ntook the day's honors in so far as\nactual advances counted, one loan\nbounding up as much as 9 points and\ntwo others advancing 2 to 3 points.\nIt was announced yesterday holders\nhad agreed to an extension of some\nnotes that matured on January 1.\nCurb Share* Higher.\nSelected oils, mining and specialty\nshares scored impressive advances in\nthe curb market and the majority of\nactive shares found enough support\nto end comfortably higher.\nGains of 1 to 2 points were regis\ntered by Creole Petroleum at 27, United\nLight Power preferred, 24; Alumi\nnum Co., 84^2, and Newmont Mining,\n65. Lesser advances were posted for\nAmerican Cyanamid \"B,\u201d American\nGas Electric, Glen Alden, Fisk Rub\nber, Hudson Bay, International Petro\nleum and Electric Bond 4b Share.\nA few laggards dotted the list. Gulf\nOil ended lower at 39?; and Niagara\nHudson Power lost \u00bb/8 at 8 >4. Pioneer\nGold and Humble Oil were unchanged.\nCATTLEINCREASES\nLARGEST IN SOUTH\nHuge Crains in Beef and Milk In\ndustry Shown Since Start of\nA. A. A. in 1933.\nBy the Associated Press.\nAgriculture Department surveys\nshowed yesterday that Southern States\nhave outstripped the Nation as a\nwhole in expansion of the beef and\nmilk cattle industry since inaugura\ntion of the farm adjustment program\nin 1933. v\nThe number of all cattle, including\ndairy, in 13 Southern States increased\nfrom 18,616.000 in 1832 to 20,051,000\nin 1937, while the number in the Na\ntion as a whole increased only 906,000\nto a 1937 total of 66,676,000.\nThe number of dairy cattle increased\n4.3 per cent in the South compared\nwith one-fifth of 1 per cent for the\nNation as a whole.\nThe number of cattle in Southern\nStates in 1932 and 1937, respectively,\nwere reported as follows:\nVirginia, 816.000 and 852,000; North\nCarolina, 594,000 and 651,000.\n\nSTEEL IMPOSTS DOWN.\nThe Commerce Department says\nImports of iron and steel products\ninto the United States dropped to\n23,985 tons worth $1,847,484 in No\nvember\u2014the lowest volume for any\nmonth aince April, 1M6.\nAND MAY HEAVEN PROTECT THE GOOD NINETY PER CENT.\nGENERAL MOTORS\nSALES DECREASE\nWorld Total in December\nSlumps, but Year\u2019s\nVolume Higher.\nB\u00bb the AMKlitfA Freea.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8 \u2014World sales\nof General Motors Corp. cars In De\ncember showed a sharp decrease un\nder December, 1936, but sales for all\nof 1937 were 3.9 per cent above the\nfigure for the preceding year, the\ncompany announced today.\nDecember sales to dealers In the\nUnited f^fates and Canada, together\nwith shipments overseas, totaled 160,\n444 units, against 193,136 in Novem\nber and 239,114 in December, 1936.\nFor the year the total was 2.116.897,\ncompared with 2,037,690 in 1936.\nDecember sales to consumers in the\nUnited States totaled 89.682 cars,\ncompared with 117.387 in November\nand 173.472 in December, 1936.\nFor the year sales to consumers in\nthe United States totaled 1,534,215, a\ndecrease of 7.3 per cent from the\n1,720.213 reported the preceding year.\nSales to dealers in the United\nStates for the month ran to 108,232\nunits, against 153.184 in November\nand 197,065 a year ago. Sales for\n1937 totaled 1,680,024, against 1,682,\n594 in 1936.\nBUILDING FACES\nADVERSE FACTORS\nTrade Uncertainty, Weak Mar\nket* and High Costs Expected\nto Restrict Activity.\nRrecisl Dispatch to Tht Star.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8\u2014Uncertainty\nover the business outlook, weakness\nin commodity and security prices, and\nhigh building costs\u2014are all factors\nlikely to restrict construction activity\nand building rehabilitation over the\ncoming months, according to Poor's\nIndustry and Investment Surveys.\nHowever, the improvement in con\nstruction earlier in 1937 should permit\nthe average building material com\npany to report a satisfactory earnings\ngain over 1936, despite poor final quar\nter results.\n\u201cWith construction activity for the\nfirst six months of 1938 promising to\nbe materially below 1937 levels, un\nfavorable earnings comparisons are in\nprospect for the period,\u201d states the\nsurvey. \"However, more encouraging\nresults are anticipated for the second\nhalf, by which time, recession is ex\npected to have run its course.\n\u201cNevertheless, earnings for the full\nyear will be somewhat under 1937.\nReflecting stimuli provided by the Fed\neral Government, residential construc\ntion during the year is likely to fare\nbetter than any other major branch\nof building activity.\n\u201cThe longer-term outlook for build\ning material and construction com\npanies is favorable. Building activity\nis well below pre-depression levels and\na great pent-up demand exists.\u201d\nCLEARING HOUSE ISSUES\nREPORT AT NEW YORK\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8.\u2014The weekly\nstatement of the New York Clearing\nHouse shows: Total surplus and un\ndivided profits increased 814,387,400;\ntotal net demand deposits (average)\nincreased 841,449,000; time deposits\n(average) decreased 810,337,000; clear\nings week ending today, 83.945,307,\n895; clearing* week ending December\n81 (five days), 83,074,348,448.\nEarnings\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8 (/P).\u2014Corporate\nearnings statements released during\nthe week, showing profits per common\nshare, included:\nJK Works Ended December 18.\n3937. 3P36.\nMasonite a .58 .65\nNovember 30 Qoarter.\nTrek-Hughes Gold .OP .12\nThree Months October 81.\n\u25a0lee Prw Lt_ .21 .21\nUnited Gas _ 1.68* .03\nSix Months October 31.\nOlidden Co _ .78 2.49\nYear November 30.\nEly Walker Dry Goods _ 1.38 4.11\nGenl Water Gas k El_ .95 .99\nInti Shoe 1.87 2.51\nYear October 31.\nDiv'co Twin Truck _ .50 .49\nLee Rubber ft Tire 2.31 2.19\nYear September 30.\nBackstay Welt 2.30 1.62\nCuban-American Sugar _ _ .74 .65\nYork Ice Machinery _3.61 tC.73\n\u2022On second preferred.\ntOn preferred.\nINVESTMENT* COMPANY\nSTOCK AVERAGE GAINS\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 8.\u2014Investment\nj companies common stock prices ad\nvanced sharply last week, according\nto the averages compiled by Distrib\nutors Group, Inc.\nThe average for the common stocks\nI for 10 leading management companies\ninfluenced by the leverage factor stood\nat 11.15 at the close of January 7,\ncompared with 9.61 on December 31.\ni The average for five mutual-type\ni investment funds closed at 11.00 on\ni January 7, compared with 10.54 on\nDecember 31.\nSANTA FE AUTHORIZED\nTO ISSUE CERTIFICATES\nBy the Associated Press\u2019\nThe Interstate Commerce Commis\nsion yesterday authorized the Atchi\nson, Topeka Santa Fe Railway to\nissue $3,900,000 series B, 2 Vi per cent\nequipment trust certificates.\nThe certificates will be sold at\n$101.57 and accrued dividends. Pro\nceeds of the issue will be used to pur\nchase new rolling stock.\nHeavy Buying at Chicago\nExposition Regarded\nas Good Sign.\nB\u00bb the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. Jan. 8.\u2014Encouraging\nstatements came from the Winter\nHome Furnishings Exposition today,\nwhere the furniture manufacturing in\ndustry is attempting a recovery from\nthe recession that followed the big\nJuly wholesale markets.\nLeaders in the industry estimated\n$30,000,000 would be spent by re\ntailers in buying up stocks for spring\nand summer trade, according to Law\nrence H. Whiting, president of the\nFurniture Mart.\nThe largest home furnishing gains\nwere reported by the major appliance\ndivision, he said, which experienced\nsharply increased sales in washers,\nironers, ranges, refrigerators, radios,\nfans and other products.\n\u201cBuying at the market the past\nweek has been substantial, and the\nindustry expects 1938 to be a satis\nfactory year.\u201d he said.\nWhiting estimated proportions of\nthe home furnishings market this\nyear will reach $2,500,000,000. with\nfurniture and appliances accounting\nfor $1,000,000,000 each.\nFurniture manufacturers were esti\nmated to have had a half billion\ndollar production in 1937, the best\nsince 1929 and compared with $430,\n000,000 in 1936.\nWOOD PULP DEMAND UP.\nBERLIN, N. H., Jan. 8 (Special).\u2014\nAn increase of 1,900 per cent in 12\nyears has been recorded in world con\ni sumption of wood pulp used in rayon\nand staple fiber, according to Brown\nCo., New England\u2019s largest pulp and\npaper producer. Consumption has\ngrown from 50,000 tons in 1925 to\n950,000 tons in 1937.\nHow Is Business?\nShoroing Current Business Activity Compared With\nthe Same Week a Year Ago.\n_ JAN. FIN WAR ARNI MAY JUN\u00ab JULY Au\u00bb. \u00bb\u00abRT. OCT. NOT PfCTMRgR\n19J7\n+5** Present\n+40* \u2014r Business\nHlffllfiilllllilillilll A*\u00b0\n-10* \u2014+-\u2014|-I\"\nGENERAL BUSINESS ACTIVITY for tb. country Indicated by Book Doblta outaldo\nNo Y- City. Shaded areas show week of activity above the corretpoodlai week\nprevious year. Black areaa ladlcate decllaes Iron saaae weeks twelve months earlier*\nACTIVITY BY FEDERAL RESERVE DISTRICTS\nChoek Tranaactlooo compared with tho earn, week a year ago\nLEADING BAROMETERS\nShowing Trend of Important Factor* Chang#\nPraaont Trend From Year Ago\nBusiness In Dollars (Checks Cashed) Downward g.g\nEmployment (Dept, of Labor). Downward 3.3\nWages (Dept, of Labor). Downward 1.5\nCoot of Living (Ind. Conf. Board)... Downward 4. 3.7\nWholesale Prices (Fisher\u2019s Index)... Downward 3.9\nAgricultural Prices (Bureau of Labor) Downward _ n'.i\nMovement of Goods (Car Loadings). Downward _\nRetail Trade (Fed. Res. Board). Downward _ 3.1\nBuilding Contracts (F. W. Dodge).. Downward 4. 1.0\nFailures (Dun\u2019s). Upward 4* 16.7\nBond Prices (Dow-Jones). Downward \u201411.8\nStock Prices (Composite Dow-Jones) Downward 38.9\n_Stock Mkt. Vol. (Shares Traded)... Upward 10.5\nAH rights monad, Cambridge Associates, Boston\nBUSINESS HAILS\nSIEEL GAINS AND\nRETAIL PICK-UP\nMotor Production Climbs.\nPower Output and Load\nings Decline.\nRECESSION DISPLAYS\nLEVELING-OFF SIGNS\nDun Bradstreet Reports Janu\nary Store Sales Are Proving\nEncouraging Surprise.\nBv THOMAS E. FLANAGAN,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer,\nA revival in steel production and\nquickening retail sales in some regions\nwere cited by observers of the na\ntional business scene during the week\njust, closed as indications of a leveling\nolT In the recession.\nThe motor industry stepped up op\nerations along with steel makers. Elec\ntric power output and freight carload\nlngs declined.\nThe Associated Press index of in\ndustrial activity stood at, 741 com\npared with 74.9 the week before and\n102 in the like week last year.\nThe Commerce Department In Its\nweekly survey of business In 36 cities\nsaid trade moved into the new year\n\u201cunder somewhat mixed conditions.\u201d\nIn New York City retail trade made\n\"a very good comparative showing.\u201d\nChicago business was spotty although\nquality stores reported good volume.\n\"In many cities of the country, how\never, trade continued very much in\nthe doldrums,\u201d the survey said.\nOn the other hand, Dun Brad\nstreet said \u201cJanuary thus far has been\nan encouraging surprise to retailers.\u201d\nCarriers Order Steel.\nThe steel industry boost in operation\nwas the first since mid-September.\nProduction was estimated at 25.6 per\ncent of capacity, compared with 13 2\nthe week previous. 27 5 a month ago\nand 79 4 in the like 1937 week.\nTrade observers said railroad de\nmand for steel, although subnormal\nfor this time of year, was a bright\nspot. Construction activity afforded\nlittle new business. Despite improved\noutputs of automobiles during the\nweek, it was reported steel men were\nnot expecting much new business\nfrom this source.\nMotor production increased to 54.\n084 units from 49.550 the preceding\nweek. This compared with 92,142 in\nthe corresponding period last year,\nWard's automotive reports said.\nFreight carloadings in the week\nended January 1 totaled 457.359, the\nAssociation of American Railroads\nreported. This was a decline of 0 7\nof 1 per cent from the previous week\nand a drop of 22.3 per cent from the\nlike week a year ago. The downturn\nwas more than seasonal, traffic ex\nperts said, caused primarily by slower\nshipments of industrial products, par\nticularly in the less-than-carlot classi\nfication.\nPower Output Lags.\nProduction of electric power in the\nfinal week of 1937 was estimated F.t\n2,000,000,000 kilowatt hours by th?\nEdison Electric Institute, This com\npared with a revised total of 2.0R.i.\n186.000 in the preceding week and\n2.080.954.000 in the comparable period\nof the year before. It was noted there\nwere moderate gains in demand for\nelectricity in the Middle Atlantic, West\nCentral and Pacific Coast regions, but\nthat other districts, including the cen\ntral industrial, used less power.\nA report in industrial circles that\nexcessive inventories in many fields\nhad been worked off sounded a cheer\nful note. Tills, business men said,\nwould help clear the path for the usual\nspring production advance.\nOn the New York Stock Exchange\nprices pushed ahead agaiast occasional\nselling flurries. Heavy industry shares\nmuch of the time were out in front,\naided by Wall Street expectations of\nheavy armaments spending.\nThe bond market, except for railroad\nloaas, gave a fair account of itself.\nCarrier issues slumped when the Erie\nSystem omitted interest payments, but\nrecovered when the Reconstruction\nFinance Corp. granted a loan to the\nBaltimore Ohio to tide it over finan\ncial difficulties.\nRaw material price trends were\nmixed.\nT\nI. C. C. OFFICIAL BACKS\nPLANS FOR NEW HAVEN\nBj Ihe Associated Press.\nAn Interstate Commerce Commis\nsion examiner approved yesterday as\n\u2018lair and equitable-\u2019 a method pro\nposed by the trustees for segregating\nearnings of the New York, New\nHaven <fc Hartford Railroad System.\nThe segregation Is being made to\ndetermine what treatment should be\naccorded various classes of security\nholders in the reorganization of the\nsystem.\nExaminer Harvey H. Wilkinson\nsaid the trustees\u2019 method of allocating\nrevenues and expenses between vari\nous mortgaged and leased lines In the\nNew Haven System \u201cis as fair and\nequitable as circumstances will per\nmit.\"\nDECLINE IS REVEALED\nIN TRANSIT REVENUES\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK. Jan. 8.\u2014Revenues for\nthe transit Industry for the week end\ning January l, 1938, baaed on tele\ngraphic reports received from a repre\nsentative group of transit operating\ncompanies, showed a moderate de\ncrease over last year.\nTransit Journal's revenue Indicator\nstands at 97.96, which represents a loss\nof 2 04 per cent over the corresponding\nweek in 1936.\nFor the week ending December 25,\n1937, the indicator was ioi.04.\nAfter showing a moderate improve\nment over 1936 for the week ended\nChristmas Day. the indicator again\ndipped below 100 for ths week ended'\non New Year Day.","height":"31348","width":"22672"}}
